# No Dense Template Literals

When a template literal contains formatted values, ternary expressions, or chained method calls, extract each piece into a named local variable before the template. The template itself should read like plain text.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — formatting, ternary, and chaining all crammed into one line
lines.push(`MA200: $${Math.round(onchain.sma200dUsd).toLocaleString("en-US")} ${market.priceUsd >= onchain.sma200dUsd ? "🟢" : "🔴"}`)

// ✅ GOOD — each concern named, template reads cleanly
const ma200 = `$${Math.round(onchain.sma200dUsd).toLocaleString("en-US")}`
const ma200Signal = market.priceUsd >= onchain.sma200dUsd ? "🟢" : "🔴"
lines.push(`MA200: ${ma200} ${ma200Signal}`)
```

This applies to template literals in `push`, `join`, JSX, log statements, and anywhere else.
